Coding plan:
"### File Structure
```
ContentPublishingHub/
│
├── app.py
├── requirements.txt
├── README.md
│
├── data/
│   ├── users.txt
│   ├── articles.txt
│   ├── article_versions.txt
│   ├── approvals.txt
│   ├── workflow_stages.txt
│   ├── comments.txt
│   └── analytics.txt
│
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── create_article.html
│   ├── edit_article.html
│   ├── version_history.html
│   ├── my_articles.html
│   ├── published_articles.html
│   ├── content_calendar.html
│   └── article_analytics.html
│
└── static/
    ├── css/
    │   └── styles.css
    ├── js/
    │   └── scripts.js
    └── img/
        └── (featured images and other assets)
```

### File Descriptions
```
- app.py
  The main Flask application file containing all backend routes, logic for reading/writing data files, version control, content scheduling, analytics, and rendering templates. Since the system is not highly complex, consolidating backend code here simplifies maintenance.

- requirements.txt
  Lists Python dependencies, primarily Flask and any other required packages.

- README.md
  Documentation for setup, running the app, and overview of features.

- data/
  Directory containing all persistent data files in text format as specified:
  - users.txt: User information.
  - articles.txt: Article metadata and status.
  - article_versions.txt: Version history of articles.
  - approvals.txt: Approval workflow data.
  - workflow_stages.txt: Workflow configuration.
  - comments.txt: Editorial comments on article versions.
  - analytics.txt: Article engagement metrics.

- templates/
  HTML templates for each page as per specification:
  - dashboard.html: Main landing page with overview and navigation.
  - create_article.html: Article creation editor.
  - edit_article.html: Article editing with version tracking.
  - version_history.html: Viewing and restoring article versions.
  - my_articles.html: User’s article list with filters.
  - published_articles.html: Public content library.
  - content_calendar.html: Scheduled publication timeline.
  - article_analytics.html: Engagement metrics display.

- static/
  Static assets served by Flask:
  - css/styles.css: Stylesheet for consistent UI design.
  - js/scripts.js: JavaScript for client-side interactivity.
  - img/: Folder for featured images and other media assets.
```
This structure supports modular development, easy testing starting from the Dashboard page, and clear separation of concerns between backend logic, templates, static assets, and data storage."

